An '''isodesmic crystal''' is a [[crystal]] in which all the [[chemical bond|bonds]] have the same [[electrostatic]] [[valency (chemistry)|valency]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Pfennig|first1=Brian|title=Principles of Inorganic Chemistry|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=-twqBwAAQBAJ|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|accessdate=3 May 2016}}</ref> This means that all the bonds are of the same strength. [[Diamond]]s and [[halite]] have isodesmic crystals. The opposite of an isodesmic crystal is an [[anisodesmic crystal]], in which [[anion]]s more strongly bonded to central coordinating [[cation]]. [[Graphite]] is an example of an anisodesmic crystal.
