{{Infobox University |name = Kigumba Petroleum Institute |image = |motto = |established = {{birth year and age|2009}} |type = Public |chancellor = '''Prof. Charles Kwesiga''' |vice_chancellor ='''Justine Odong'''<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/Business/Markets/Current-oil-gas-training-below-standards-experts-/688606-4493862-ae4q73/index.html |title=Current oil and gas training below standards - experts |access-date=23 April 2018 |date=23 April 2018 |newspaper=[[Daily Monitor]] |first=Eronie |last=Kamukama | location=Kampala}}</ref> |city = [[Kigumba]] |country = [[Uganda]] |coor ={{coord|01|50|34|N|32|01|09|E|display=inline, title}} |students = 88 (2011) |staff = |campus = Rural |website = [https://www.upik.ac.ug/ Homepage] |pushpin_map = Uganda }}
'''Kigumba Petroleum Institute''', also referred to as [[Uganda Petroleum Institute]] or as '''Uganda Petroleum Institute, Kigumba (UPIK)''', is a [[government|government-owned]], national center for training, research and consultancy in the field of petroleum exploration, recovery, refinement and responsible utilization in [[Uganda]].<ref>{{cite web|date=5 August 2014 | url=http://www.oilinuganda.org/features/social-impacts/petroleum-institute-admits-third-intake-introduces-new-courses.html | title=Petroleum institute receives third intake, introduces new courses |access-date=23 April 2018 |publisher=Oil in Uganda | last=Beatrice Ongode | first=and Flavia Nalubega | location=Kampala}}</ref>
==Location== The institute is located approximately {{convert|4|mi|km}}, by road, north of the town of [[Kigumba]], off of the [[Kigumba]]–[[Karuma]] Road, in [[Kiryandongo District]], [[Western Region, Uganda|Western Uganda]]. This location lies approximately {{convert|41|km|0}}, by road, northeast of [[Masindi]], the nearest large town in the [[Bunyoro sub-region|sub-region]].<ref>{{cite web|access-date=23 April 2018 |date=23 April 2018 | url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Masindi%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Uganda%20Petroleum%20Institute%20Kigumba%2C%20Kigumba%2C%20Uganda&dt1=ChIJt2KmdvjRehcRz4gqPEH1vzQ&dt2=ChIJVVVVVbbqehcROpjNJdbpNmI |title=Distance between Masindi, Uganda and Uganda Petroleum Institute Kigumba, Kigumba, Uganda |publisher=Globefeed.com |author=Globefeed.com}}</ref> Uganda Petroleum Institute is located approximately {{convert|203|km|0}}, by road, northwest of [[Kampala]], Uganda's capital and largest city.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=23 April 2018 |url=https://distancecalculator.globefeed.com/Uganda_Distance_Result.asp?fromplace=Uganda%20Post%20Office%2C%20Kampala%20Road%2C%20Kampala%2C%20Uganda&toplace=Uganda%20Petroleum%20Institute%20Kigumba%2C%20Kigumba%2C%20Uganda&dt1=ChIJQ6vCjIC8fRcRO0xjOZ4-3Qc&dt2=ChIJVVVVVbbqehcROpjNJdbpNmI |title=Distance between Uganda Post Office, Kampala Road, Kampala, Uganda and Uganda Petroleum Institute Kigumba, Kigumba, Uganda |date=23 April 2018 |publisher=Globefeed.com |author=Globefeed.com}}</ref> The coordinates of the Institute's campus are: 01°50'34.0"N, 32°01'09.0"E (Latitude:1.842778; Longitude:32.019167).<ref>{{google maps|access-date=23 April 2018 |title=Location of Uganda Petroleum Institute, Kigumba, Kiryandongo District, Uganda | url=https://www.google.co.ug/maps/place/1%C2%B050'34.0%22N+32%C2%B001'09.0%22E/@1.8409831,32.0175007,986m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m5!3m4!1s0x0:0x0!8m2!3d1.8427778!4d32.0191667?hl=en}}</ref>
==History== The institute was established in 2009<ref>{{cite web| url=http://ugandaradionetwork.com/a/story.php?s=37384| title=Petroleum Institute Lacks Space To Accommodate <nowiki>[sic]</nowiki> Students| accessdate=11 June 2014|publisher=Uganda Radio Network (URN)| first=Fredrick|last=Kivabulaya|date=6 October 2011}}</ref> and admitted the first batch of students in 2010, with the objective of training personnel in petroleum-related skills, at certificate, diploma and undergraduate levels.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.monitor.co.ug/News/Education/-/688336/874940/-/111j7js/-/index.html|title=Oil technical School Set to Open In Kigumba District|last=Patience Ahimbisibwe|first=and Steven Ariong|date=8 March 2010|publisher=[[Daily Monitor]]|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> In 2011, increased budgettary allocations were made towards the elevation of the institute from a vocational school to a fully-fledged International University. Financial assistance to the tune of US$8 million (UGX:20 billion), will be sought from the [[World Bank]] and [[Irish Aid]], to achieve this goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.observer.ug/index.php?option=com_content&task=view&id=13802&Itemid=106|title=Education Budget Focus Shifts to Job Creation|first=Moses|last=Talemwa|date=12 June 2011|publisher=[[The Observer (Uganda)]]|accessdate=11 June 2014}}</ref> In November 2011, the [[Uganda Government]] began the process of elevating the Institute to University status.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.parliament.go.ug/enewsletter/index.php/home/view/118/ |title=Motion for a Resolution of Parliament to Establish Uganda Petroleum Institute Kigumba (UPIK) Under the Universities and Other Tertiary Institutions Act, 2001, As Amended |date=10 November 2011 |accessdate=11 June 2014 |publisher=[[Parliament of Uganda|Uganda Parliament ENewslettler]] |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924064412/http://www.parliament.go.ug/enewsletter/index.php/home/view/118/ |archivedate=24 September 2015 |df= }}</ref>
==Recent developments== In 2014, the institute introduced five new internationally recognized programs to graduate "highly qualified and specialized" technicians needed by oil companies across the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newvision.co.ug/news/656490-petroleum-institute-starts-new-international-courses.html|title=Petroleum Institute Starts New International Courses|publisher=[[New Vision]]|date=11 June 2014|accessdate=11 June 2014|first=Pascal|last=Kwesiga}}</ref> The new plan proposes wide ranging overhaul of the curriculum and the introduction of five new diploma courses in oil studies. The institute also plans to work in close collaboration with the Ugandan oil industry to graduate over 220 students annually by the year 2019, up from 54 in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|accessdate=10 December 2014| url=http://www.observer.ug/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=32683:-kigumba-petroleum-institute-to-introduce-five-new-oil-courses|title=Kigumba Petroleum Institute To Introduce Five New Oil Courses|date=9 July 2014| first=.|last=Observer Media Limited|publisher=[[The Observer (Uganda)]]}}</ref>
