{{chembox | Verifiedfields = changed | Watchedfields = changed | verifiedrevid = 444215513 | ImageFile = NbO2structure.jpg | ImageSize = | IUPACName = niobium(IV) oxide, niobium dioxide | OtherNames = niobium(IV) oxide, columbium dioxide |Section1={{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo_Ref = {{cascite|correct|??}} | CASNo = 12034-59-2 | PubChem = 82839 | EINECS = 234-809-7 | InChI = 1S/Nb.2O | SMILES = O=[Nb]=O }} |Section2={{Chembox Properties | Formula = NbO<sub>2</sub> | MolarMass = 124.91 g/mol | Appearance = bluish black | Density = | MeltingPtC = 1915 | MeltingPt_ref = <ref name = "Gupta">C. K. Gupta, A. K. Suri, S Gupta, K Gupta (1994), ''Extractive Metallurgy of Niobium'', CRC Press, {{ISBN|0-8493-6071-4}}</ref> | BoilingPt = | Solubility = }} |Section3={{Chembox Structure | CrystalStruct = [[Tetragonal]], [[Pearson symbol|tI96]] | SpaceGroup = I4<sub>1</sub>/a, No. 88 }} }} '''Niobium dioxide''', is the [[chemical compound]] with the [[chemical formula|formula]] NbO<sub>2</sub>. It is a bluish black [[non-stoichiometric]] solid with a composition range of NbO<sub>1.94</sub>-NbO<sub>2.09</sub><ref name = "Gupta"/> It can be prepared by reacting Nb<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> with H<sub>2</sub> at 800–1350&nbsp;°C.<ref name = "Gupta"/> An alternative method is reaction of Nb<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub> with Nb powder at 1100&nbsp;°C.<ref name = "Patnaik">Pradyot Patnaik (2002), ''Handbook of Inorganic Chemicals'',McGraw-Hill Professional, {{ISBN|0-07-049439-8}}</ref>
The room temperature form NbO<sub>2</sub> has a tetragonal, [[titanium dioxide|rutile]]-like structure with short Nb-Nb distances indicating Nb-Nb bonding.<ref>Wells A.F. (1984) ''Structural Inorganic Chemistry'' 5th edition Oxford Science Publications {{ISBN|0-19-855370-6}}</ref> High temp form also has a [[titanium dioxide|rutile]]-like structure with short Nb-Nb distances.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.1006/jssc.1994.1334|title=A Powder Neutron Diffraction Study of Semiconducting and Metallic Niobium Dioxide|year=1994|author=Bolzan, A|journal=Journal of Solid State Chemistry|volume=113|pages=9|last2=Fong|first2=Celesta|last3=Kennedy|first3=Brendan J.|last4=Howard|first4=Christopher J.|bibcode = 1994JSSCh.113....9B }}</ref> Two high pressure phases have been reported one with a [[titanium dioxide|rutile]]-like structure, again with short Nb-Nb distances, and a higher pressure with [[baddeleyite]]-related structure.<ref>{{cite journal| doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.59.13650| title=High-pressure structural phase transitions in semiconducting niobium dioxide| year=1999|author1=Haines, J. |author2=Léger, J. M. |author3=Pereira, A. S. | journal=Physical Review B| volume=59| pages=13650| issue=21 |bibcode = 1999PhRvB..5913650H }}</ref>
NbO<sub>2</sub> is insoluble in water and is a powerful reducing agent, reducing [[carbon dioxide]] to carbon and [[sulfur dioxide]] to sulfur.<ref name = "Gupta"/> In an industrial process for the production of niobium metal [http://www.research.bayer.com/edition_16/16_New_capacitors.pdfx], NbO<sub>2</sub> is produced as an intermediate, by the hydrogen reduction of [[niobium pentoxide|Nb<sub>2</sub>O<sub>5</sub>]].<ref name = "Schnitter">Patent EP1524252, Sintered bodies based on niobium suboxide, Schnitter C, Wötting G</ref> The NbO<sub>2</sub> is subsequently reacted with magnesium vapour to produce niobium metal.<ref>Method for producing tantallum/niobium metal powders by the reduction of their oxides by gaseous magnesium, US patent 6171363 (2001), Shekhter L.N., Tripp T.B., Lanin L.L. (H. C. Starck, Inc.)</ref>
